<emphasis id="B972EA991978FFBF6A8BA1F67168FE3F" bold="true" box="[189,324,401,427]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB9368B1978FFBF6A8BA1A77216FE69" blockId="88.[189,1399,448,509]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081978FFBF684AA1A77327FE4E" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[636,779,448,474]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granditarsis">
<emphasis id="B972EA991978FFBF684AA1A77327FE4E" box="[636,779,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">granditarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘having a large tarsus’ and referring to the enlarged and flattened protarsus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
